---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, appBySlug, appPairs, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const slug = Astro.params.slug || '';
const path = Array.isArray(slug) ? slug.join('/') : slug;
const parts = path.split('/').filter(Boolean);
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
function channelApps(){ return APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')); }
let valid = allPaths().includes(path);
if (!valid) return Astro.redirect('/');
const pairs = appPairs();
const primaryApps = channelApps().slice(0,12);
const operatingPrinciples = [
  'Confirm that every subscriber source records TCPA-friendly consent and a clear expectation for message type.',
  'Use Shopify order history before offering a discount; repeat buyers and first-time browsers need different reasons to act.',
  'Model cost per delivered message against gross margin, not just attributed revenue inside the app dashboard.',
  'Build quiet-hour, frequency, and suppression rules before launch week rather than after unsubscribes spike.',
  'Keep email nearby for education-heavy moments so SMS can stay short, useful, and rare.'
];
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={`/${path}`}>
  <section class="border-b border-cyan-300/30 py-14">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="badge">{site.primaryKeyword} · signal-room guide</span>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-4">{title}</h1>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-4xl text-xl text-cyan-100">{desc} This page is written for Shopify operators who want SMS to create real retention lift without annoying the list. The analysis is tailored to {site.angle}, and it treats message timing, consent, attribution, and margin as first-class buying criteria.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-white">App radar: compare the SMS stack before you install</h2><p class="mt-4 text-cyan-100">A Shopify SMS app should do more than send a campaign to a list. It should know whether the shopper abandoned checkout or only browsed, whether they bought full price or only with coupons, whether the product is replenishable, and whether a text is worth the interruption. Use this hub to move from vendor logos to operating fit.</p></div><div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{APPS.map((app,i)=><a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-sm font-black text-cyan-200">#{i+1} · {app.category}</div><h2 class="mt-2 text-2xl font-black text-white">{app.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-cyan-100">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-cyan-50">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container grid gap-8 py-12 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_330px]"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>What {app.name} does for Shopify SMS teams</h2><p>{app.shopifyFit} For searches around <strong>{site.primaryKeyword}</strong>, the real question is not whether {app.name} can send a text. The question is whether it can decide when a text deserves to exist, who should receive it, what Shopify context should shape it, and how the team will measure the result after message costs and discounts.</p><p>Strong SMS operations start with restraint. A welcome coupon, an abandoned checkout reminder, a drop alert, a replenishment nudge, a VIP early-access message, and a winback text all create different expectations. If a platform treats those moments as the same campaign object, the store eventually pays through unsubscribe rate, list fatigue, and unnecessary incentives. {app.name} should be evaluated by how clearly it separates those jobs.</p><h2>Where it fits best</h2><p>{app.name} is strongest for {app.bestFor}. It belongs on the shortlist when your store needs {site.channel} workflows connected to real order history, product interest, and customer lifecycle stage. Look carefully at how the app imports Shopify products, discount codes, checkout events, customer tags, fulfillment status, and subscription or replenishment signals. Those connections determine whether the tool becomes a revenue system or only another broadcast tab.</p><h2>Strengths</h2><ul>{app.strengths.map(s=><li>{s}</li>)}</ul><h2>Limits to watch</h2><ul>{app.limits.map(l=><li>{l}</li>)}</ul><h2>Implementation plan</h2><p>Do not start by migrating every old campaign. Start with a consent audit, then rebuild the highest-intent flows: subscriber welcome, checkout recovery, post-purchase reassurance, replenishment if relevant, VIP or launch alerts, and winback. Each flow should have a reason to use SMS instead of email. If the message needs long proof, product education, or multiple images, email should carry the weight and SMS should point to the moment only when urgency is genuine.</p><p>Before launch, document frequency caps, suppression windows, discount hierarchy, and a rule for when a customer exits the sequence. Build a weekly scorecard with revenue, conversion rate, unsubscribe rate, reply quality, gross margin after discount, and incremental lift where possible. Choose {app.name} if the platform makes that operating rhythm easier. Skip it if the interface looks polished but the team still needs spreadsheets to understand what happened.</p><h2>Buying advice</h2><p>For {site.keywordPlural}, the winning tool is the one your team will actually operate weekly. A larger feature list is not automatically better. The best SMS stack lets a merchant send fewer, sharper messages: a cart recovery text that respects purchase intent, a product launch alert reserved for engaged shoppers, and a replenishment reminder timed to usage rather than an arbitrary blast calendar.</p></article><aside class="card h-fit"><div class="text-sm font-black uppercase tracking-[.2em] text-cyan-200">Snapshot</div><dl class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-cyan-100"><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Category</dt><dd>{app.category}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Pricing</dt><dd>{app.pricing}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black text-white">Best for</dt><dd>{app.bestFor}</dd></div></dl><a class="btn btn-primary mt-6 w-full" href="https://sequenzy.com">Compare with Sequenzy</a></aside></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-white">Head-to-head SMS comparisons</h2><p class="mt-4 text-cyan-100">These pages compare operating fit rather than repeating vendor copy. Use them to decide which platform better supports your next quarter of Shopify retention work.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{pairs.map(([a,b])=><a class="card" href={`/compare/${a.slug}-vs-${b.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{a.name} vs {b.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-cyan-100">Which is better for {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()}?</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container py-12"><div class="card overflow-x-auto"><table class="data-table"><thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>{a?.name}</th><th>{b?.name}</th><th>Shopify takeaway</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>{a?.bestFor}</td><td>{b?.bestFor}</td><td>Pick based on operating model, not logo recognition.</td></tr><tr><td>Pricing</td><td>{a?.pricing}</td><td>{b?.pricing}</td><td>Model costs against list growth and message volume.</td></tr><tr><td>Strength</td><td>{a?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{b?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{site.primaryKeyword} should create revenue you can defend after costs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><article class="prose-shopify mt-8 card"><h2>Verdict for {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{a?.name} is usually better when you need {a?.bestFor}. {b?.name} is stronger when the store cares more about {b?.bestFor}. For Shopify, choose the tool that handles your highest-value lifecycle moments first: welcome, checkout recovery, post-purchase, replenishment, VIP, and winback.</p><p>The right comparison starts with the next ninety days. If the business is preparing a product drop, prioritize segmentation, list growth, early-access controls, and deliverability under volume. If the business is leaking checkout revenue, prioritize event reliability, coupon controls, and timing tests. If the business sells consumables, replenishment logic matters more than campaign templates. A generic winner does not exist; the winner is the app that turns your specific Shopify data into messages customers do not regret receiving.</p><p>If both tools look close, run a migration-risk test: can your team rebuild the top five revenue flows, segment by product and order history, preserve consent records, and read revenue by campaign without manual spreadsheet work? If not, the cheaper subscription can become the more expensive operating choice.</p><h2>Decision checklist</h2><ul>{operatingPrinciples.map(p=><li>{p}</li>)}</ul></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-white">SMS app recommendations by Shopify store type</h2><p class="mt-4 text-cyan-100">A store category changes the proper SMS cadence. Browse the guides below for category-specific implementation advice.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{s.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-cyan-100">Marketing problems: {s.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How {seg.name} should choose {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{seg.name} have to account for {seg.pain}. That changes the app shortlist: the best choice is not always the biggest platform, but the one that maps those store-specific signals into useful messages. A category with repeat purchase timing needs different automation than a category built on considered gifts or trend-driven drops.</p><p>The SMS plan should begin with customer intent. New subscribers need a concise reason to trust the brand. Cart abandoners need help finishing a decision they already started. Recent buyers need reassurance, shipping context, setup instructions, or a reason to join the next lifecycle step. Lapsed customers need a message that acknowledges prior purchase behavior instead of pretending they are brand-new.</p><h2>Recommended shortlist</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,7).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Implementation notes for {seg.name}</h2><p>Start with one money flow, one trust-building flow, and one reactivation flow. For {site.keywordPlural}, more campaigns are not automatically better. Better timing and cleaner segmentation usually beat extra sends. Use product categories, order count, AOV, last purchase date, and discount usage to prevent the list from receiving irrelevant texts.</p><p>For this segment, the safest operating rule is to define the customer benefit before the campaign copy. A text should save time, protect access, remind at the right moment, or make a decision easier. If the message only exists because the calendar has an empty slot, send an email instead or skip the send entirely.</p><h2>Measurement</h2><p>Track conversion, revenue, unsubscribes, replies, margin after incentives, and repeat purchase behavior. Segment-level analysis matters because a flow that performs well for one category can damage another. The best SMS app is the one that makes these reads visible without a manual export.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-12"><div class="mb-8 max-w-4xl"><h2 class="text-3xl font-black text-white">Use-case playbooks for Shopify SMS</h2><p class="mt-4 text-cyan-100">Each use case deserves its own trigger, suppression logic, measurement plan, and escalation path to email or support.</p></div><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{USE_CASES.map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black text-white">{u.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-cyan-100">Use {site.primaryKeyword.toLowerCase()} to {u.job}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Best approach for {u.name}</h2><p>The job of {u.name} is to {u.job}. For {site.primaryKeyword}, that means using Shopify events, product context, consent, and customer history to decide who gets the message and when. SMS should not be the default channel; it should be the channel selected when speed, simplicity, or access matters more than long-form persuasion.</p><p>A good implementation starts with a trigger definition, a reason to text, a suppression rule, and a success metric. For abandoned cart, the trigger is high intent and the metric is recovered margin after discount. For replenishment, the trigger is likely usage and the metric is repeat purchase timing. For VIP campaigns, the trigger is customer value and the metric is early-access conversion without irritating loyal buyers.</p><h2>Apps to consider</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a>: {a.shopifyFit}</li>)}</ul><h2>Execution sequence</h2><p>Draft the SMS in plain language, then remove every word that does not help the customer act. Add a destination that matches the promise: checkout, product page, account page, subscription portal, or support thread. Test timing against behavior rather than a fixed assumption. A same-hour cart text can be useful for some products and aggressive for others; a replenishment reminder can be perfect at thirty days for one SKU and useless for another.</p><h2>What to measure</h2><p>Measure recovered revenue, unsubscribe rate, repeat purchase rate, margin after discounts, reply quality, and revenue by segment. Avoid judging {u.name} only by opens or attributed clicks. If a flow increases sales while teaching subscribers to wait for coupons, the dashboard may look healthy while the brand becomes less profitable.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; const alts=APPS.filter(a=>a.slug!==app.slug).slice(0,8); return <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Why Shopify stores look for {app.name} alternatives</h2><p>{app.name} is a credible option, but it is not always the right fit for every store searching for {site.primaryKeyword}. Common reasons to compare alternatives include pricing, channel mix, migration workload, segmentation depth, compliance workflow, and how much Shopify-specific reporting the team needs.</p><p>An alternative search should start with the pain that forced the review. If costs rose because message volume grew, inspect pricing and suppression tools. If campaigns feel generic, inspect segmentation and Shopify event depth. If the team cannot explain performance, inspect reporting. If the brand is moving from SMS-only tactics to lifecycle retention, inspect whether the app coordinates with email and post-purchase education.</p><h2>Best alternatives</h2><ul>{alts.map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><h2>Selection rule</h2><p>Do not switch tools just for a cleaner interface. Switch when the alternative makes an important Shopify workflow easier to launch, easier to measure, or cheaper to scale. The migration should improve consent records, event reliability, segmentation, and operating rhythm. Otherwise the store only trades one learning curve for another.</p><p>Before committing, rebuild one flow in the new tool on paper: trigger, audience, exclusions, copy, destination, discount logic, reporting, and owner. If the alternative cannot make that flow simpler or more profitable, keep looking.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'guides' && <section class="container py-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Shopify SMS app selection framework</h2><p>Pick {site.primaryKeyword} by matching your business model to lifecycle jobs. New stores need capture, welcome, cart recovery, and first purchase campaigns. Growing stores need segmentation, post-purchase education, replenishment, winback, and deliverability discipline. Larger brands need governance, experimentation, attribution, and channel coordination.</p><p>The core framework is simple: prove consent, define the customer moment, choose the channel, protect margin, and measure the result. SMS is powerful because it is immediate, but that same immediacy makes weak campaigns feel intrusive. A strong Shopify SMS program sends fewer texts than a weak one and earns more from each interruption.</p><h2>Internal linking map</h2><ul><li><a class="link" href="/apps">All apps</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/compare">Comparison pages</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart guide</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/for/fashion">Fashion store guide</a></li></ul><h2>Operating principles</h2><ul>{operatingPrinciples.map(p=><li>{p}</li>)}</ul></article></section>}

  <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>SMS operating manual for this page</h2><p>Read this page as a buying memo, not a vendor brochure. The right Shopify SMS app should make a merchant more careful and more precise. It should reveal when a subscriber opted in, what they were doing before the opt-in, which products or collections created intent, and how recently the customer bought. Without that context, a text is only a loud version of a generic promotion.</p><p>Before adopting any recommendation, map the first month of use. Week one should confirm consent capture, branded sending identity, quiet hours, suppression rules, and the events flowing from Shopify. Week two should launch or repair the highest-intent flow, usually welcome or checkout recovery. Week three should add a post-purchase or replenishment moment that improves the customer experience without demanding another immediate order. Week four should review results and remove anything that produced opt-outs, replies showing confusion, or sales that depended on excessive discounting.</p><p>The strongest stores also assign ownership. Someone must approve offers, someone must watch deliverability and compliance, someone must coordinate email so SMS is not forced to explain too much, and someone must compare attributed revenue with actual order quality. If everyone can send, nobody protects the channel. A good tool supports roles, previews, testing, and reporting, but the operating habit matters just as much as the feature.</p><p>Use the internal links on this site to move from broad research to a concrete decision. App pages explain individual fit. Comparison pages force tradeoffs. Store-type pages translate SMS into category problems. Use-case pages turn abstract features into flows. The goal is not to install the most famous app; the goal is to build a Shopify SMS program that customers still trust six months from now.</p></article></section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app=appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Deep SMS review notes for {app.name}</h2><p>A meaningful {app.name} review starts with the interruption budget. Shopify shoppers may welcome a text when it protects access, saves a cart, confirms a useful detail, or reminds them at exactly the right replenishment moment. They will not tolerate a channel that behaves like a louder newsletter. Evaluate {app.name} by asking whether it helps the store send fewer, sharper messages rather than more generic campaigns.</p><p>Consent is the first operational test. The platform should make opt-in source, disclosure language, keyword capture, checkout consent, and suppression status easy to inspect. A merchant should be able to prove why a subscriber is eligible before a campaign goes out. If the tool hides consent behind broad list labels, the store inherits compliance and trust risk. That matters even more during Black Friday, launch weeks, and high-volume promotions when the temptation to over-send is strongest.</p><p>The second test is Shopify context. {app.name} should understand checkout abandonment, products viewed, products purchased, discount history, order count, average order value, fulfillment status, and replenishment windows. Those fields decide whether a text is useful. A cart reminder for a high-AOV product may need reassurance and financing language; a consumable reorder reminder may need timing; a launch alert may need VIP priority and inventory urgency. Without those distinctions, the app is only a messaging pipe.</p><p>Cost control is the third test. SMS has a direct cost per send, so attributed revenue alone can be misleading. Review revenue after message fees, carrier fees, discount cost, and the long-term effect on opt-outs. A campaign that looks profitable in the dashboard may still be weak if it trains full-price buyers to wait for incentives or pushes unsubscribes from loyal customers. The best SMS apps expose enough reporting to make that tradeoff visible.</p><p>Finally, judge {app.name} by weekly maintainability. Can a marketer adjust quiet hours, pause a flow, change offer logic, exclude recent buyers, and coordinate with email without a developer? Can support or retention teams inspect replies and customer state quickly? If the answer is yes, the app can become part of a respectful revenue system. If not, the store may end up with an expensive broadcast tool that customers slowly learn to ignore.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b]=parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Expanded {a?.name} vs {b?.name} SMS decision process</h2><p>Compare {a?.name} and {b?.name} by building the same SMS journey in both systems. Start with consent capture, then abandoned checkout, post-purchase, replenishment, VIP launch, and winback. For each journey, write the trigger, delay, quiet-hour rule, exclusion logic, offer, destination, and reporting view. The better Shopify SMS app is the one that makes those decisions explicit and easy to maintain.</p><p>The winner may change by business model. A fashion brand needs drop alerts, segmentation by size or collection interest, and launch-day suppression discipline. A supplement store needs replenishment timing and careful claim language. A high-AOV store needs proof, support paths, and fewer aggressive discounts. A wholesale store may need account-specific ordering prompts. Do not choose a platform because it wins a generic checklist; choose the one that fits the store’s commercial rhythm.</p><p>Pricing must include message volume and mistakes. If one app makes it easy to over-message, the hidden cost appears in carrier fees, opt-outs, lost trust, and lower customer lifetime value. If another app encourages better suppression and clearer intent, it may create more profit with fewer sends. Model a realistic month with sale campaigns, automations, transactional-adjacent updates, and list growth before declaring either platform cheaper.</p><p>Reporting should also be tested. Ask whether each app shows revenue by message, flow, segment, product, and customer stage. Then compare that with Shopify orders and margin. SMS attribution can exaggerate impact when a buyer was already likely to purchase. A strong tool helps the merchant understand actual behavior change, not only last-click credit.</p><p>End the comparison by choosing the app your team will use responsibly. SMS performance compounds when the channel is protected: clear consent, tight segmentation, useful timing, respectful frequency, and coordination with email. The wrong app may produce fast revenue while burning the list. The right app creates a durable channel customers still trust after the launch calendar gets busy.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Long SMS strategy for {seg.name}</h2><p>{seg.name} need SMS behavior shaped around {seg.pain}. That pressure changes what deserves a text. A campaign should either protect timely access, remove purchase friction, remind a customer when action is useful, or create a personal shortcut to support or checkout. If a message does not do one of those jobs, email or no message may be the better choice.</p><p>The first step is to define customer moments by urgency. Browsing interest, cart abandonment, fulfillment updates, product usage, reorder timing, and VIP access all carry different expectations. The SMS app should let the team separate those moments by product, collection, order count, discount history, and consent source. Without that separation, {seg.name} risk sending messages that feel convenient for the brand but irrelevant to the customer.</p><p>Copy should stay short, but the strategy behind it should not be shallow. A good text for this segment tells the shopper why now matters and sends them to the exact next step. That could be a cart, a product page, a subscription portal, a size guide, a back-in-stock item, or a support thread. The destination matters because SMS has little room to explain context; the landing experience must finish the job.</p><p>Measurement should include conversion, replies, unsubscribes, margin after incentives, repeat purchase timing, and whether SMS changes email engagement. Some categories can tolerate more frequent alerts during launches; others need stricter restraint. The app should make frequency and quiet-hour rules easy enough that the team does not rely on memory or last-minute manual exclusions.</p><p>For {seg.name}, the right Shopify SMS app is the one that makes restraint operational. It should support urgent revenue moments while preserving customer trust. If the tool mainly encourages larger blasts, it may create short-term sales and long-term fatigue. Choose the platform that helps the team prove every text deserves to interrupt.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Full SMS execution plan for {u.name}</h2><p>The job of {u.name} is to {u.job}, but SMS should only be used when immediacy improves the outcome. Start by naming the customer benefit. The text might preserve a cart, announce limited access, remind someone before a product runs out, or make a high-value decision easier. If the benefit is vague, the message probably belongs in email.</p><p>Build the flow around a precise trigger and a strict suppression rule. Recent buyers, open support issues, refunded customers, VIP segments, subscription customers, and people already receiving another urgent text may need exclusions. Quiet hours and frequency caps should be configured before launch, not after complaints arrive. The strongest SMS apps make these guardrails visible at the campaign level.</p><p>The message should use plain language and one clear action. Do not make SMS carry the whole education burden. If {u.name} requires proof, explanations, ingredients, sizing, comparison, or detailed terms, use the text to route the customer to a page or email that can do that work. SMS is the prompt, not the brochure.</p><p>Shopify data should decide timing. A replenishment reminder should follow product usage patterns, not a universal delay. A cart text should respect product price, discount state, and recent emails. A VIP message should understand customer value and inventory pressure. A winback text should know what the customer bought before and whether a new offer is relevant.</p><p>Measure success after costs and trust signals. Count conversion, order quality, message cost, discount cost, opt-outs, reply sentiment, and repeat purchase behavior. A good {u.name} SMS flow should make the customer journey simpler and more timely. If it only lifts sales by being louder than email, it will eventually weaken the channel it depends on.</p></article></section> })()}
  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Replacing {app.name} without damaging SMS trust</h2><p>A search for {app.name} alternatives should begin with a trust audit. Identify whether the problem is cost, consent visibility, segmentation, reporting, reply handling, support, or channel coordination. Each weakness points to a different replacement. Moving platforms without naming the issue can leave the store with the same over-sending habits in a new dashboard.</p><p>Before migration, export or document every opt-in source, keyword, form, checkout disclosure, list, segment, suppression, quiet-hour rule, campaign, automation, and reply workflow. SMS history is sensitive because the customer gave permission for a specific kind of communication. The alternative must preserve that context and make it easier to inspect, not harder.</p><p>Rebuild one flow first. Choose checkout recovery, replenishment, VIP access, or winback and compare the old and new logic line by line. Who enters, who is excluded, when does the text send, what does it cost, what destination does it use, and how is revenue reported? The replacement should make at least one important workflow clearer or more profitable than {app.name}.</p><p>Coordinate the move with email. Many SMS failures happen because the text is forced to carry too much information or because email and SMS send conflicting offers. The best alternative should let the merchant use SMS for urgency and email for context, proof, and longer persuasion. That balance protects both channels.</p><p>The right alternative leaves the store with fewer blasts, cleaner consent records, stronger segmentation, and a better weekly review habit. If the new app only looks simpler while hiding the same risks, keep looking. SMS is too interruptive to migrate casually.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app=appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>{app.name} SMS operating worksheet</h2><p>Evaluate {app.name} with a live-message rehearsal. Create one profile from a checkout opt-in, one from a popup promising launch alerts, one recent buyer, and one lapsed customer. Confirm the app can show why each person is eligible, what product or checkout event created the opportunity, what quiet-hour rule applies, and which texts should be suppressed. This is the practical difference between an SMS-native system and a blast tool with a Shopify integration.</p><p>The implementation sequence should protect trust before revenue. First confirm consent sources, STOP handling, branded links, reply routing, and compliance language. Then rebuild one urgent flow such as abandoned checkout or VIP launch access. Add replenishment only when the product has a defensible usage window. Add winback only when the team can distinguish lapsed loyal customers from one-time gift buyers and coupon hunters. A high-volume migration should wait until those checks are boring.</p><p>Migration risks are specific to SMS. Losing opt-in source, disclosure history, keyword context, suppression lists, quiet-hour settings, or reply workflows can make the new app look operationally simple while increasing trust risk. Before moving a large segment into {app.name}, compare who would receive a message in the old and new systems and calculate cost after message fees, carrier fees, incentive cost, and expected opt-outs.</p><h3>Score before sending</h3><ul><li><strong>Consent visibility:</strong> every recipient can be traced to permission and expectation.</li><li><strong>Trigger accuracy:</strong> checkout, cart, product, fulfillment, and replenishment events are current and understandable.</li><li><strong>Cost discipline:</strong> the app makes small, profitable audiences easier than broad sends.</li><li><strong>Human fallback:</strong> replies, support questions, and complaints have an owner.</li></ul></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b]=parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Deep SMS comparison scorecard for {a?.name} and {b?.name}</h2><p>Compare the two apps by building five SMS scenarios: checkout recovery, replenishment, back-in-stock, VIP launch access, and winback. For each scenario, document opt-in source, trigger, delay, quiet-hour handling, exclusion rules, message cost, offer, destination, and the report a manager will review. The winner is the app that makes restraint easier to operate, not the one that makes broadcasting fastest.</p><p>{a?.name} should win if it handles the store's highest-risk SMS moment with clearer consent, sharper targeting, better cost controls, or easier replies. {b?.name} should win if its workflow better supports the next campaign calendar. A fashion launch, supplement reorder, high-AOV cart, and wholesale reorder prompt need very different SMS behavior. A generic feature checklist hides those differences.</p><p>Run a failure rehearsal before buying. Imagine a text sends inside quiet hours, inventory sells out after a launch alert, a coupon reaches recent full-price buyers, or support receives angry replies. Which app helps the team stop, inspect, and repair the issue fastest? Shopify SMS tools earn trust when the store is under pressure, not only when a small test campaign performs well.</p><h3>Decision rubric</h3><ul><li>Consent proof and suppression controls.</li><li>Shopify event freshness and product context.</li><li>Message economics after fees, discount, and opt-outs.</li><li>Ability to coordinate with email so SMS stays brief and urgent.</li></ul></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-16"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>SMS build sheet for {u.name}</h2><p>Begin {u.name} by proving that SMS is the right channel. The message should save time, protect access, recover a live decision, or remind the customer at a moment when action is genuinely useful. If the play needs detailed proof, education, ingredient explanation, sizing advice, or complex terms, use email or a landing page to carry that context and let SMS act as a precise pointer.</p><p>Define the trigger and exclusions with real Shopify states. Recent buyers, subscription customers, refunded orders, VIPs, support cases, lapsed customers, and discount-only shoppers may all need different handling. Quiet hours and frequency caps should be configured before launch. The first QA pass should preview real profiles, not hypothetical segments, because most SMS mistakes come from edge cases that looked obvious after the send.</p><p>Measurement should include conversion, order quality, message cost, discount cost, opt-outs, replies, support load, and repeat purchase movement. A {u.name} text that creates revenue but spikes unsubscribes may not be a win. A smaller flow with fewer sends can be better if it preserves channel trust and teaches the merchant which timing actually changes behavior.</p><h3>Mistakes to avoid</h3><ul><li>Using SMS because email engagement is low, rather than because immediacy helps the customer.</li><li>Sending the same coupon to new subscribers, VIPs, lapsed buyers, and recent purchasers.</li><li>Ignoring quiet hours, reply handling, and cost per delivered message.</li><li>Letting SMS and email make conflicting promises during a sale.</li></ul></article></section> })()}

